[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD involves use of a domain-specific language (DSL) using natural-language constructs (e.g., English-like sentences) that can express the behavior and the expected outcomes.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD encourages collaboration among developers, quality assurance experts, and customer representatives in a software project.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] It encourages teams to use conversation and concrete examples to formalize a shared understanding of how the application should behave.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD is considered an effective practice especially when the *problem space* is complex.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] A common misconception regarding BDD is that it supposedly is a refinement of test-driven development (TDD).
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] While it was originally derived from TDD practices, the sole purpose of BDD is to gain a *shared understanding* of the problem space and find a way to write this down in a Business Language, using Real data, whilst being Intention revealing, Essential and Focused (BRIEF).
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD combines the techniques of TDD with ideas from domain-driven design and object-oriented analysis and design to provide software development and management teams with shared tools and a shared process to collaborate on software development.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] At a high level, BDD is an idea about how software development should be managed by both business interests and technical insight.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Its *practice* involves use of specialized tools.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Some tools specifically for BDD can be used for TDD.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The tools automate the ubiquitous language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD is a process by which DSL structured natural-language statements are converted into executable tests.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The result is executable specification eventually forming Living Documentation: Requirements that are also the first acceptance tests that drive your software development (Acceptance test-driven development).
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Starting from this point, many people developed BDD frameworks over a period of years, finally framing it in terms of a communication and collaboration framework for developers, QA and non-technical or business participants in a software project.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that software tests should be named in terms of desired *behavior*.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Borrowing from agile software development the "desired behavior" in this case consists of the requirements set by the business — that is, the desired behavior that has business value for whatever entity commissioned the software unit under construction.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Within BDD practice, this is referred to as BDD being an "outside-in" activity.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] TDD does not differentiate tests in terms of high-level software requirements, low-level technical details or anything in between.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] One way of looking at BDD therefore, is that it is an evolution of TDD which makes more specific choices.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Another BDD suggestion relates to *how* the desired behavior should be specified.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests using a semi-formal format for behavioral specification which is borrowed from user story specifications from the field of object-oriented analysis and design.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The scenario aspect of this format may be regarded as an application of Hoare logic to behavioral specification of software using the domain-specific language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD suggests that business analysts and software developers should collaborate in this area and should specify behavior in terms of user stories, which are each explicitly documented.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD does not require how this information is formatted, but it does suggest that a team should decide on a relatively simple, standardized format with the above elements.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] It also suggests that the scenarios should be phrased declaratively rather than imperatively — in the business language, with no reference to elements of the UI through which the interactions take place.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] This format is referred to in Cucumber as the Gherkin language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD borrows the concept of the *ubiquitous language* from domain driven design.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] A ubiquitous language is a (semi-)formal language that is shared by all members of a software development team — both software developers and non-technical personnel.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The language in question is both used and developed by all team members as a common means of discussing the domain of the software in question.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] In this way BDD becomes a vehicle for communication between all the different roles in a software project.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] A common risk with software development includes communication breakdowns between Developers and Business Stakeholders.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD uses the specification of desired behavior as a ubiquitous language for the project Team members.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] This is the reason that BDD insists on a semi-formal language for behavioral specification: some formality is a requirement for being a ubiquitous language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] In addition, having such a ubiquitous language creates a domain model of specifications, so that specifications may be reasoned about formally.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] This model is also the basis for the different BDD-supporting software tools that are available.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The example given above establishes a user story for a software system under development.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] This user story identifies a stakeholder, a business effect and a business value.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] It also describes several scenarios, each with a precondition, trigger and expected outcome.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Each of these parts is exactly identified by the more formal part of the language (the term **Given** might be considered a keyword, for example) and may therefore be processed in some way by a tool that understands the formal parts of the ubiquitous language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Most BDD applications use text-based DSLs and specification approaches.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] However, graphical modeling of integration scenarios has also been applied successfully in practice, e.g., for testing purposes.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Much like TDD, BDD may involve using specialized tooling.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] BDD requires not only test code as does TDD, but also a document that describes behavior in a more human-readable language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] This requires a two-step process for executing the tests, reading and parsing the descriptions, and reading the test code and finding the corresponding test implementation to execute.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] This process makes BDD more laborious for developers.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Proponents suggest that due to its human-readable nature the value of those documents extends to a relatively non-technical audience, and can hence serve as a communication means for describing requirements ("features").
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] In principle, a BDD support tool is a testing framework for software, much like the tools that support TDD.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] However, where TDD tools tend to be quite free-format in what is allowed for specifying tests, BDD tools are linked to the definition of the ubiquitous language.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The ubiquitous language allows business analysts to document behavioral requirements in a way that will also be understood by developers.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The principle of BDD support tooling is to make these same requirements documents directly executable as a collection of tests.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] If this cannot be achieved because of reasons related to the technical tool that enables the execution of the specifications, then either the style of writing the behavioral requirements must be altered or the tool must be changed.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] A separate subcategory of behavior-driven development is formed by tools that use specifications as an input language rather than user stories.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Specification tools don't use user stories as an input format for test scenarios but rather use functional specifications for units that are being tested.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] These specifications often have a more technical nature than user stories and are usually less convenient for communication with business personnel than are user stories.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Such a specification may exactly specify the behavior of the component being tested, but is less meaningful to a business user.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] As a result, specification-based testing is seen in BDD practice as a complement to story-based testing and operates at a lower level.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] Specification testing is often seen as a replacement for free-format unit testing.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The "three amigos", also referred to as a "Specification Workshop", is a meeting where the product owner discusses the requirement in the form of specification by example with different stakeholders like the QA and development team.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The key goal for this discussion is to trigger conversation and identify any missing specifications.
[src:gherkin/behavior-driven-development] The discussion also gives a platform for QA, development team and product owner to converge and hear out each other's perspective to enrich the requirement and also make sure if they are building the right product.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Cucumber was originally written in the Ruby programming language and was originally used exclusively for Ruby testing as a complement to the RSpec BDD framework.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Cucumber now supports a variety of different programming languages through various implementations, including Java and JavaScript.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] There is a port of Cucumber to .NET called SpecFlow, now superseded by Reqnroll.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Gherkin is the language that Cucumber uses to define test cases.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] It is designed to be non-technical and human readable, and collectively describes use cases relating to a software system.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] The purpose behind Gherkin's syntax is to promote behavior-driven development practices across an entire development team, including business analysts and managers.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] It seeks to enforce firm, unambiguous requirements starting in the initial phases of requirements definition by business management and in other stages of the development lifecycle.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] In addition to providing a script for automated testing, Gherkin's natural language syntax is designed to provide simple documentation of the code under test.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Gherkin currently supports keywords in dozens of languages.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Syntax is centered around a line-oriented design, similar to that of Python.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] The structure of a file is defined using whitespace and other control characters.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Lines starting with `#` are considered comments, and can be placed anywhere in a file.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Instructions are any non-empty and non-comment line.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] They consist of a recognized Gherkin keyword followed by a string.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] All Gherkin files have the `.feature` file extension.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] They contain a single Feature definition for the system under test and are an executable test script.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Cucumber comes with a built-in command line interface that covers a comprehensive list of instructions.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Like most command line tools, cucumber provides the `--help` option that provides a summary of arguments the command accepts.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Cucumber command line can be used to quickly run defined tests.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] It also supports running a subset of scenarios by filtering tags.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] The above command helps in executing only those scenarios that have the specified `@tag-name`.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Arguments can be provided as a logical `OR` or `AND` operation of tags.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Apart from tags, scenarios can be filtered on scenario names.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] The above command will run only those scenarios that contain the word 'logout'.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] It is also useful to be able to know what went wrong when a test fails.
[src:gherkin/cucumber-software] Cucumber makes it easy to catch bugs in the code with the `--backtrace` option.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:gherkin/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-languages] In order to allow Gherkin to be written in a number of languages, the keywords have been translated into multiple languages.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-languages] To improve readability and flow, some languages may have more than one translation for any given keyword.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-languages] You can find all translation of Gherkin on GitHub.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-languages] This is also the place to add or update translations.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-languages] A list of the currently supported languages and their keywords can be found below.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Gherkin uses a set of special keywords to give structure and meaning to executable specifications.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Each keyword is translated to many spoken languages; in this reference we'll use English.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Most lines in a Gherkin document start with one of the keywords.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Comments are only permitted at the start of a new line, anywhere in the feature file.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] They begin with zero or more spaces, followed by a hash sign (`#`) and some text.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Block comments are currently not supported by Gherkin.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Either spaces or tabs may be used for indentation.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The recommended indentation level is two spaces.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The trailing portion (after the keyword) of each step is matched to a code block, called a step definition.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Please note that some keywords *are* followed by a colon (`:`) and some *are not*.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] If you add a colon after a keyword that should not be followed by one, your test(s) will be ignored.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Each line that isn't a blank line has to start with a Gherkin *keyword*, followed by any text you like.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The only exceptions are the free-form descriptions placed underneath `Example`/`Scenario`, `Background`, `Scenario Outline` and `Rule` lines.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Gherkin is localised for many spoken languages; each has their own localised equivalent of these keywords.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The purpose of the `Feature` keyword is to provide a high-level description of a software feature, and to group related scenarios.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The first primary keyword in a Gherkin document must always be `Feature`, followed by a `:` and a short text that describes the feature.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can add free-form text underneath `Feature` to add more description.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] These description lines are ignored by Cucumber at runtime, but are available for reporting (they are included by reporting tools like the official HTML formatter).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The name and the optional description have no special meaning to Cucumber.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Their purpose is to provide a place for you to document important aspects of the feature, such as a brief explanation and a list of business rules (general acceptance criteria).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The free format description for `Feature` ends when you start a line with the keyword `Background`, `Rule`, `Example` or `Scenario Outline` (or their alias keywords).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can place tags above `Feature` to group related features, independent of your file and directory structure.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can only have a single `Feature` in a `.feature` file.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Free-form descriptions (as described above for `Feature`) can also be placed underneath `Example`/`Scenario`, `Background`, `Scenario Outline` and `Rule`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can write anything you like, as long as no line starts with a keyword.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Descriptions can be in the form of Markdown - formatters including the official HTML formatter support this.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The (optional) `Rule` keyword has been part of Gherkin since v6.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The purpose of the `Rule` keyword is to represent one *business rule* that should be implemented.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] It provides additional information for a feature.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] A `Rule` is used to group together several scenarios that belong to this *business rule*.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] A `Rule` should contain one or more scenarios that illustrate the particular rule.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] This is a *concrete example* that *illustrates* a business rule.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The keyword `Scenario` is a synonym of the keyword `Example`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can have as many steps as you like, but we recommend 3-5 steps per example.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Having too many steps will cause the example to lose its expressive power as a specification and documentation.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] In addition to being a specification and documentation, an example is also a *test*.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] As a whole, your examples are an *executable specification* of the system.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Each step starts with `Given`, `When`, `Then`, `And`, or `But`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Cucumber executes each step in a scenario one at a time, in the sequence you’ve written them in.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] When Cucumber tries to execute a step, it looks for a matching step definition to execute.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Keywords are not taken into account when looking for a step definition.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] This means you cannot have a `Given`, `When`, `Then`, `And` or `But` step with the same text as another step.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] `Given` steps are used to describe the initial context of the system - the *scene* of the scenario.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] It is typically something that happened in the *past*.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] When Cucumber executes a `Given` step, it will configure the system to be in a well-defined state, such as creating and configuring objects or adding data to a test database.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The purpose of `Given` steps is to **put the system in a known state** before the user (or external system) starts interacting with the system (in the `When` steps).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Avoid talking about user interaction in `Given`'s.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] If you were creating use cases, `Given`'s would be your preconditions.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] It's okay to have several `Given` steps (use `And` or `But` for number 2 and upwards to make it more readable).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] `When` steps are used to describe an event, or an *action*.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] This can be a person interacting with the system, or it can be an event triggered by another system.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Most software does something people could do manually (just not as efficiently).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Try hard to come up with examples that don't make any assumptions about technology or user interface.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Imagine it's 1922, when there were no computers.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Implementation details should be hidden in the step definitions.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] `Then` steps are used to describe an *expected* outcome, or result.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The step definition of a `Then` step should use an *assertion* to compare the *actual* outcome (what the system actually does) to the *expected* outcome (what the step says the system is supposed to do).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] An outcome *should* be on an **observable** output.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] That is, something that comes *out* of the system (report, user interface, message), and not a behaviour deeply buried inside the system (like a record in a database).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] While it might be tempting to implement `Then` steps to look in the database - resist that temptation!
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You should only verify an outcome that is observable for the user (or external system), and changes to a database are usually not.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Gherkin also supports using an asterisk (`*`) in place of any of the normal step keywords.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] This can be helpful when you have some steps that are effectively a *list of things*, so you can express it more like bullet points where otherwise the natural language of `And` etc might not read so elegantly.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Occasionally you'll find yourself repeating the same `Given` steps in all of the scenarios in a `Feature`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Since it is repeated in every scenario, this is an indication that those steps are not *essential* to describe the scenarios; they are *incidental details*.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can literally move such `Given` steps to the background, by grouping them under a `Background` section.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] A `Background` allows you to add some context to the scenarios that follow it.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] It can contain one or more `Given` steps, which are run before *each* scenario, but after any Before hooks.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] A `Background` is placed before the first `Scenario`/`Example`, at the same level of indentation.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can only have one set of `Background` steps per `Feature` or `Rule`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] If you need different `Background` steps for different scenarios, consider breaking up your set of scenarios into more `Rule`s or more `Feature`s.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] For a less explicit alternative to `Background`, check out conditional hooks.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The `Scenario Outline` keyword can be used to run the same `Scenario` multiple times, with different combinations of values.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The keyword `Scenario Template` is a synonym of the keyword `Scenario Outline`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] We can collapse these two similar scenarios into a `Scenario Outline`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] A `Scenario Outline` must contain one or more `Examples` (or `Scenarios`) section(s).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Its steps are interpreted as a template which is never directly run.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Instead, the `Scenario Outline` is run *once for each row* in the `Examples` section beneath it (not counting the first header row).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The steps can use `<>` delimited *parameters* that reference headers in the examples table.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Cucumber will replace these parameters with values from the table *before* it tries to match the step against a step definition.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can use parameters in `Scenario Outline` descriptions as well.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] You can also use parameters in multiline step arguments.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] In some cases you might want to pass more data to a step than fits on a single line.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] For this purpose Gherkin has `Doc Strings` and `Data Tables`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] `Doc Strings` are handy for passing a larger piece of text to a step definition.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] In your step definition, there’s no need to find this text and match it in your pattern.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] It will automatically be passed as the last argument in the step definition.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Indentation of the opening `"""` is unimportant, although common practice is two spaces in from the enclosing step.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The indentation inside the triple quotes, however, is significant.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Each line of the Doc String will be dedented according to the opening `"""`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Indentation beyond the column of the opening `"""` will therefore be preserved.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] This might be familiar for those used to writing with Markdown.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Whilst all current versions of Cucumber support backticks as the delimiter, many tools like text editors don't (yet).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] It's possible to annotate the DocString with the type of content it contains.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Whilst all current versions of Cucumber support content types as the delimiter, many tools like text editors don't (yet).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Just like `Doc Strings`, `Data Tables` will be passed to the step definition as the last argument.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] If you want to use a newline character in a table cell, you can write this as `\n`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] If you need a `|` as part of the cell, you can escape it as `\|`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] And finally, if you need a `\`, you can escape that with `\\`.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Cucumber provides a rich API for manipulating tables from within step definitions.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] See the Data Table API reference reference for more details.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] The language you choose for Gherkin should be the same language your users and domain experts use when they talk about the domain.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Translating between two languages should be avoided.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] This is why Gherkin has been translated to over 70 languages .
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] A `# language:` header on the first line of a feature file tells Cucumber what spoken language to use - for example `# language: fr` for French.
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] If you omit this header, Cucumber will default to English (`en`).
[src:gherkin/gherkin-reference] Some Cucumber implementations also let you set the default language in the configuration, so you don't need to place the `# language` header in every file.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Automation provides many benefits over manual testing.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] For API testing, tests drive the SUT via its application programming interface (API).
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Compared to manual testing, automated API testing often can execute a relatively large number of cases in a relatively short time.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] For GUI testing, tests drive the SUT via its graphical user interface (GUI) by generating events such as keystrokes and mouse clicks.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Automated GUI testing can be challenging to develop, but can run much faster than a human could perform the same testing.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] When automated testing is in place, regression testing can be a relatively quick and easy operation.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Instead of a significant outlay of human time and effort, a regression test run could require nothing more than a push of a button and even starting the run can be automated.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] The following are notable testing techniques categorized as test automation.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to assess the business risk of releasing the SUT.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] The scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] For model-based testing, the SUT is modeled and test cases can be generated from it to support no code test development.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Some tools support the encoding of test cases as plain English that can be used on multiple operating systems, browsers, and smart devices.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Test-driven development (TDD) inherently includes the generation of automation test code.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Unit test code is written while the SUT code is written.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] When the code is complete, the tests are complete as well.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] A review of 52 practitioner and 26 academic sources found that five main factors to consider in test automation decision are: system under test (SUT), scope of testing, test toolset, human and organizational topics, cross-cutting factors.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] The factors most frequently identified were: need for regression testing, economic factors, and maturity of SUT.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] While the reusability of automated tests is valued by software development companies, this property can also be viewed as a disadvantage as it leads to a plateau effect, where repeatedly executing the same tests stops detecting errors.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Testing tools can help automate tasks such as product installation, test data creation, GUI interaction, problem detection (consider parsing or polling agents equipped with test oracles), defect logging, etc., without necessarily automating tests in an end-to-end fashion.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] To support coded automated testing, the test engineer or software quality assurance person must have software coding ability.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Some testing techniques such as table-driven and no-code can lessen or alleviate the need for programming skill.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] A test automation framework provides a programming environment that integrates test logic, test data, and other resources.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] The framework provides the basis of test automation and simplifies the automation effort.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Using a framework can lower the cost of test development and maintenance.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] If there is change to any test case then only the test case file needs to be updated and the driver script and startup script will remain the same.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] A framework is responsible for defining the format in which to express expectations, providing a mechanism to hook into or drive the SUT, executing the tests, and reporting results.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] A test automation interface is a platform that provides a workspace for incorporating multiple testing tools and frameworks for system/integration testing.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] A test automation interface may simplify the process of mapping tests to business criteria without coding.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] A test automation interface may improve the efficiency and flexibility of maintaining tests.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] The parser is present to parse the object files coming from the object repository into the test specific scripting language.
[src:gherkin/test-automation] Collection of UI/Application object data recorded by the testing tool while exploring the SUT.
